So I want to start-- I think
most people here know it,

00:01:40.820 --> 00:01:46.270
but for posterity and for the
videotape, tell us your story.

00:01:46.270 --> 00:01:47.240
I mean, who are you?

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:48.835
How did you get to this chair?

00:01:48.835 --> 00:01:50.960
LUVVIE AJAYI: By being a
professional troublemaker.

00:01:50.960 --> 00:01:52.829
That's how I got to this chair.

00:01:52.829 --> 00:01:53.370
I'm a writer.

00:01:53.370 --> 00:01:54.030
I'm a speaker.

00:01:54.030 --> 00:01:55.260
I'm a techie.

00:01:55.260 --> 00:01:57.410
And I have been
blogging for 13 years.

00:01:57.410 --> 00:01:59.240
I started blogging in 2003.

00:01:59.240 --> 00:02:02.474
I was in college, and I was
peer-pressured into doing it,

00:02:02.474 --> 00:02:04.890
because my friends were like,
you should start a web blog.

00:02:04.890 --> 00:02:06.610
And I was like, OK.

00:02:06.610 --> 00:02:10.825
So I went to Xanga.com
and started a web--

00:02:10.825 --> 00:02:11.700
and I started a blog.

00:02:11.700 --> 00:02:13.140
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: That's not
Zingo, that's Xanga, right?

00:02:13.140 --> 00:02:14.140
LUVVIE AJAYI: Xanga, OK?

00:02:14.140 --> 00:02:16.706
Remember Xanga, like next to
Friendster and everything?

00:02:16.706 --> 00:02:17.580
And I start blogging.

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:19.829
I was talking about college
life and all my randomness

00:02:19.829 --> 00:02:22.670
and shenanigans and who I
was beefing with that day--

00:02:22.670 --> 00:02:24.290
nothing interesting.

00:02:24.290 --> 00:02:27.400
And basically I have my
college career chronicled,

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:29.260
which for good and all bad.

00:02:29.260 --> 00:02:31.690
I read it, and I was
like, this is awful.

00:02:31.690 --> 00:02:34.010
When I graduated from
college, I deleted that blog,

00:02:34.010 --> 00:02:36.051
and I was like, I'm going
to start something new.

00:02:36.051 --> 00:02:38.970
And I go to Blogspot,
fire up this new blog,

00:02:38.970 --> 00:02:41.150
called it Luvvi's Random Rants.

00:02:41.150 --> 00:02:44.040
And I was talking about all
things pop culture, television,

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:46.890
anything I felt like talking
about, but not myself anymore.

00:02:46.890 --> 00:02:50.090
So that's how blogging
for me started.

00:02:50.090 --> 00:02:52.532
And it basically took
on a life of its own.

00:02:52.532 --> 00:02:53.990
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
And you were born

00:02:53.990 --> 00:02:55.624
in Africa, grew up in Chicago.

00:02:55.624 --> 00:02:56.415
Tell us that story.

00:02:56.415 --> 00:02:57.206
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:02:57.206 --> 00:02:58.650
So I was born in Nigeria.

00:02:58.650 --> 00:03:00.127
And when I was nine, we moved--

00:03:00.127 --> 00:03:01.710
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
Are you got shouting

00:03:01.710 --> 00:03:02.910
for Nigeria or Chicago?

00:03:02.910 --> 00:03:06.660
LUVVIE AJAYI: [LAUGHING]
Right, yes-- Nigeria.

00:03:06.660 --> 00:03:10.550
So we moved to Chicago
when I was nine.

00:03:10.550 --> 00:03:12.190
Nobody told me we were moving.

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:13.820
I thought we were
going on vacation.

00:03:13.820 --> 00:03:15.345
[LAUGHTER]

00:03:15.345 --> 00:03:17.470
And then I started school,
and I was like, oh, this

00:03:17.470 --> 00:03:18.390
means we're staying.

00:03:18.390 --> 00:03:20.617
Oh.

00:03:20.617 --> 00:03:22.200
And it was a big
culture shock for me,

00:03:22.200 --> 00:03:25.090
because I went from
never having to be

00:03:25.090 --> 00:03:28.230
the new girl, like
my best friend was

00:03:28.230 --> 00:03:31.190
the niece of the person who
owned the private school I went

00:03:31.190 --> 00:03:31.734
to.

00:03:31.734 --> 00:03:33.650
I'd been going to that
school since I was two.

00:03:33.650 --> 00:03:37.270
So walking in a room and seeing
people who didn't look like me

00:03:37.270 --> 00:03:39.640
and having to reintroduce
myself and basically

00:03:39.640 --> 00:03:43.460
take on a new persona was
a huge shock to my system.

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:45.560
But, yeah, I had
this accent, too.

00:03:45.560 --> 00:03:47.860
Well, no, not this
accent, actually.

00:03:47.860 --> 00:03:50.280
I had a major Nigerian accent.

00:03:50.280 --> 00:03:52.890
And I end up having
to-- I lost it

00:03:52.890 --> 00:03:56.890
consciously by
mimicking my classmates

00:03:56.890 --> 00:03:59.024
and like trying to repeat
what they were saying

00:03:59.024 --> 00:04:00.190
and how they were saying it.

00:04:00.190 --> 00:04:03.440
And then by high school
my accent was mostly gone.

00:04:03.440 --> 00:04:04.440
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Right.

00:04:04.440 --> 00:04:05.331
She thinks it's gone.

00:04:05.331 --> 00:04:05.830
Anyway--

00:04:05.830 --> 00:04:06.663
LUVVIE AJAYI: Right!

00:04:06.663 --> 00:04:07.341
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:07.341 --> 00:04:07.840
Right.

00:04:07.840 --> 00:04:08.650
You're right.

00:04:08.650 --> 00:04:09.520
No, I hear it.

00:04:09.520 --> 00:04:10.590
I'm super Nigerian, yeah.

00:04:10.590 --> 00:04:11.964
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
So do you think

00:04:11.964 --> 00:04:15.840
that experience of sort of being
a transplant at nine years old

00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:20.670
and being different
informs some of who you are

00:04:20.670 --> 00:04:24.020
and your ability to
stand outside of things

00:04:24.020 --> 00:04:26.165
and tell it like it is?

00:04:26.165 --> 00:04:29.090
Is that part of why you're you?

00:04:29.090 --> 00:04:30.200
LUVVIE AJAYI: Well, yeah.

00:04:30.200 --> 00:04:34.340
So the tell-it-like-it-is-ness
that is me is my Nigerian-ness

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:35.370
in its true essence.

00:04:35.370 --> 00:04:40.060
Like Nigerians, we're not a
great filtering people, OK?

00:04:40.060 --> 00:04:41.960
We're not the ones
who are like, oh,

00:04:41.960 --> 00:04:45.320
let me make sure I coat it
in all types of nice things.

00:04:45.320 --> 00:04:46.905
We just say what we feel.

00:04:46.905 --> 00:04:48.530
Like if you come like
my family dinner,

00:04:48.530 --> 00:04:50.654
we spend the whole time
laughing at each other.

00:04:50.654 --> 00:04:52.070
Like somebody will
walk in wearing

00:04:52.070 --> 00:04:53.330
a sweater that's not cute--

00:04:53.330 --> 00:04:54.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:54.350 --> 00:04:58.177
--and somebody will always be
like, why do you have that on?

00:04:58.177 --> 00:04:59.260
It's just how we function.

00:04:59.260 --> 00:05:02.360
And in my writing, my
writing is essentially

00:05:02.360 --> 00:05:05.470
who I am in real life in print.

00:05:05.470 --> 00:05:08.340
Because I want people who know
me to read my work and be like,

00:05:08.340 --> 00:05:09.590
OK, I actually hear her voice.

00:05:09.590 --> 00:05:10.990
That's exactly her.

00:05:10.990 --> 00:05:15.100
So how I write very much
translates to who I am.

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:19.360
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: That's
interesting, and in your youth

00:05:19.360 --> 00:05:20.930
from like nine
through high school

00:05:20.930 --> 00:05:25.400
and things like that, were
you extroverted, class clown?

00:05:25.400 --> 00:05:30.000
Like before in the
pre-blogging, pre-college years,

00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:31.580
what was that like for you?

00:05:31.580 --> 00:05:34.610
LUVVIE AJAYI: I have been
the class clown forever.

00:05:34.610 --> 00:05:37.370
This person that you see is
who I was in high school.

00:05:37.370 --> 00:05:40.810
I still have the same friends
that I did in high school.

00:05:40.810 --> 00:05:44.320
And we were just a
goofy group of people.

00:05:44.320 --> 00:05:46.610
We'll be in the hallway
just acting the fool

00:05:46.610 --> 00:05:50.420
or playing spades
in the lunchroom

00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:52.960
and just spend all
the time laughing.

00:05:52.960 --> 00:05:55.860
And basically my
group of friends

00:05:55.860 --> 00:05:57.970
are a really good
reflection of who I am.

00:05:57.970 --> 00:05:59.407
Like you think I'm funny?

00:05:59.407 --> 00:06:00.990
You come to brunch
with us, and you'll

00:06:00.990 --> 00:06:04.550
be in tears, because none of
them have behavior or sense.

00:06:04.550 --> 00:06:06.600
So it's just how I've been.

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:09.820
And being able to have it
translate to my writing

00:06:09.820 --> 00:06:11.907
has been great,
because literally I

00:06:11.907 --> 00:06:13.990
have these friends who
have known me for 20 years,

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:16.198
and people are like, oh,
how did you find your voice?

00:06:16.198 --> 00:06:17.590
And I was like, do you see them?

00:06:17.590 --> 00:06:18.720
That's me.

00:06:18.720 --> 00:06:22.500
So it's not even a matter of
me having to find my voice.

00:06:22.500 --> 00:06:24.730
It's me just growing it up.

00:06:24.730 --> 00:06:25.230
Yeah.

00:06:25.230 --> 00:06:27.290
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: So you went
to University of Illinois.

00:06:27.290 --> 00:06:27.840
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yes.

00:06:27.840 --> 00:06:30.240
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: And I love
how she drops like 13 years,

00:06:30.240 --> 00:06:32.510
like that's a long time in
tech and stuff like that.

00:06:32.510 --> 00:06:33.870
LUVVIE AJAYI: It is!

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:37.260
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Way before you
got there, the web browser was

00:06:37.260 --> 00:06:37.990
invented there.

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:38.840
LUVVIE AJAYI: Internet Explorer.

00:06:38.840 --> 00:06:39.190
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Yes.

00:06:39.190 --> 00:06:39.510
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:06:39.510 --> 00:06:40.240
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Yeah, Mosaic.

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:41.865
LUVVIE AJAYI: That's
our claim to fame.

00:06:41.865 --> 00:06:43.900
We're very proud of
that in Illinois, yeah.

00:06:43.900 --> 00:06:45.710
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: My wife
went to school there, too.

00:06:45.710 --> 00:06:46.668
LUVVIE AJAYI: Oh, yeah.

00:06:46.668 --> 00:06:49.660
It's one of the things they tell
you when you go to orientation.

00:06:49.660 --> 00:06:52.264
And they're like,
at Illinois, we

00:06:52.264 --> 00:06:54.430
invented-- I was like,
impressive, I will come here,

00:06:54.430 --> 00:06:54.930
yes.

00:06:54.930 --> 00:06:56.360
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:57.830
This has changed
everything for me.

00:06:57.830 --> 00:06:59.020
I must be here, yes.

00:06:59.020 --> 00:07:03.050
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: And you got
into blogging while at college.

00:07:03.050 --> 00:07:06.130
And so do you think
that's how you had access?

00:07:06.130 --> 00:07:09.930
Like how did you
come to do that?

00:07:09.930 --> 00:07:13.640
LUVVIE AJAYI: So I've
always liked computers.

00:07:13.640 --> 00:07:16.310
I took computer-type
classes in school.

00:07:16.310 --> 00:07:20.860
I was a person who actually
took an Excel class for fun.

00:07:20.860 --> 00:07:23.610
So for me, I've always kind
of seen the value of computers

00:07:23.610 --> 00:07:26.700
and all these types of software.

00:07:26.700 --> 00:07:29.200
But I was also the person who
started infusing social media

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:31.060
into the work that I was doing.

00:07:31.060 --> 00:07:34.140
Like I've been an early
adopter of most platforms.

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:36.406
And blogging was
just another thing

00:07:36.406 --> 00:07:38.030
that I was kind of
an early adopter at.

00:07:38.030 --> 00:07:39.863
Because when I started
blogging, it was just

00:07:39.863 --> 00:07:42.250
playing on the internet.

00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:45.570
But I was doing it because
I thought it was fun.

00:07:45.570 --> 00:07:49.300
How I've been approaching
technology since,

00:07:49.300 --> 00:07:53.840
I have to go to the
library to get my e-mail.

00:07:53.840 --> 00:07:56.394
My first e-mail account
was a Hotmail account.

00:07:56.394 --> 00:07:59.770
[LAUGHING] And I think it
was like vetvet@hotmail.

00:07:59.770 --> 00:08:02.480
[LAUGHING] But then we had AOL.

00:08:02.480 --> 00:08:06.137
So I've seen the evolution
of the internet grow,

00:08:06.137 --> 00:08:07.220
and it's been really cool.

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:09.817
But I've always
found it valuable.

00:08:09.817 --> 00:08:11.400
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
So that first phase,

00:08:11.400 --> 00:08:13.640
you said you were sort
of blogging your college

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:15.710
experience, but then you
deleted the whole thing.

00:08:15.710 --> 00:08:16.599
LUVVIE AJAYI: Yeah.

00:08:16.599 --> 00:08:18.390
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Do
you still have a copy?

00:08:18.390 --> 00:08:19.110
LUVVIE AJAYI: I do.

00:08:19.110 --> 00:08:19.850
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: OK.

00:08:19.850 --> 00:08:20.140
LUVVIE AJAYI: In
its Comic Sans font.

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:21.264
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: So do we.

00:08:21.264 --> 00:08:22.620
We've got that in Google cache.

00:08:22.620 --> 00:08:23.430
LUVVIE AJAYI: No!

00:08:23.430 --> 00:08:24.210
[LAUGHING]

00:08:24.210 --> 00:08:25.835
BRADLEY HOROWITZ:
No, I'm just kidding.

00:08:25.835 --> 00:08:27.890
LUVVIE AJAYI: Right, like, no!

00:08:27.890 --> 00:08:29.950
No, like I had Comic
Sans font and everything.

00:08:29.950 --> 00:08:31.804
And it was like--
it was just awful.

00:08:31.804 --> 00:08:33.929
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: And it's
not up online right now?

00:08:33.929 --> 00:08:34.760
LUVVIE AJAYI: No.

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:37.320
I think I actually was
like, OK, legit, delete it.

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:39.640
But before I deleted the
blog, I like copied and pasted

00:08:39.640 --> 00:08:42.840
every single post
into a Word document.

00:08:42.840 --> 00:08:44.840
And the Word document
is giant, because it's

00:08:44.840 --> 00:08:47.580
three years of me in college
being a fool, being like,

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:48.660
oh, this is my roommate.

00:08:48.660 --> 00:08:50.590
I didn't really
like her that time.

00:08:50.590 --> 00:08:52.550
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: So
that's interesting,

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:55.530
because you're so out there
and so vulnerable and honest

00:08:55.530 --> 00:08:56.590
about things.

00:08:56.590 --> 00:08:59.760
Have you posted things
that you regret or go

00:08:59.760 --> 00:09:01.200
back and delete or edit?

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:03.720
Like what's it like
having that out there?

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:06.100
Because these days, once
you put something out there,

00:09:06.100 --> 00:09:06.890
it's out there.

00:09:06.890 --> 00:09:07.616
LUVVIE AJAYI: It's out there.

00:09:07.616 --> 00:09:07.980
BRADLEY HOROWITZ: Yeah.

00:09:07.980 --> 00:09:09.605
LUVVIE AJAYI: Well,
so here's the thing

00:09:09.605 --> 00:09:11.584
is about blogging
for so long, the good

00:09:11.584 --> 00:09:13.500
and the bad thing is it
chronicles your growth

00:09:13.500 --> 00:09:17.660
as a human being and as somebody
who thinks about the world.

00:09:17.660 --> 00:09:20.106
And so things there are
things that I wrote in 2009

00:09:20.106 --> 00:09:22.230
that I would never write
today because I vehemently

00:09:22.230 --> 00:09:24.202
disagree with myself.

