the Privilege Exercise?

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:05.220
Oh!

00:35:05.220 --> 00:35:08.226
I feel like every company in
Silicon Valley-- actually,

00:35:08.226 --> 00:35:10.350
every company in general
needs to make this happen.

00:35:10.350 --> 00:35:12.490
So the Privilege
Exercise changed my life

00:35:12.490 --> 00:35:13.764
and how I looked at the world.

00:35:13.764 --> 00:35:15.680
And I was a counseling
center paraprofessional

00:35:15.680 --> 00:35:19.920
when I was in college, trained
to be a peer counselor.

00:35:19.920 --> 00:35:24.360
But the whole first semester
was us learning about who we are

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:25.710
and the space we take up.

00:35:25.710 --> 00:35:28.520
And literally, we spent
a whole six months

00:35:28.520 --> 00:35:31.110
talking about ourselves and
who we are and unpacking it.

00:35:31.110 --> 00:35:33.690
So one thing we did was
the Privilege Exercise.

00:35:33.690 --> 00:35:38.130
So everyone starts
in the same line, OK?

00:35:38.130 --> 00:35:39.480
You start in same line.

00:35:39.480 --> 00:35:40.620
And they make a statement.

00:35:40.620 --> 00:35:42.400
You either step
forward or step back.

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:44.310
So a statement would
be something like,

00:35:44.310 --> 00:35:48.460
step forward if you've never
had to worry about somebody

00:35:48.460 --> 00:35:50.147
mispronouncing your name.

00:35:50.147 --> 00:35:50.980
People step forward.

00:35:50.980 --> 00:35:55.070
Step back if you've
sometimes worried about where

00:35:55.070 --> 00:35:56.350
your next meal is coming from.

00:35:56.350 --> 00:35:57.620
Somebody steps back.

00:35:57.620 --> 00:36:00.130
Step up if you can marry
the person you love.

00:36:00.130 --> 00:36:02.366
So it's a series of questions.

00:36:02.366 --> 00:36:03.740
Sometimes it's
like 20 questions.

00:36:03.740 --> 00:36:04.860
Sometimes it's 50.

00:36:04.860 --> 00:36:07.000
At the end of the Privilege
Exercise, they say,

00:36:07.000 --> 00:36:10.200
stop and look around
the room and see

00:36:10.200 --> 00:36:12.390
where you are in
relation to other people.

00:36:12.390 --> 00:36:16.780
So sometimes I found
myself higher to the front

00:36:16.780 --> 00:36:19.020
than I actually
imagined I would be.

00:36:19.020 --> 00:36:22.020
And some of my classmates in
the back, and I was like, wow,

00:36:22.020 --> 00:36:23.460
you're behind me?

00:36:23.460 --> 00:36:27.090
And it gives you the perspective
of understanding like, OK.

00:36:27.090 --> 00:36:28.690
So the Privilege
Exercise, you get

00:36:28.690 --> 00:36:32.125
to actually get to
figure out, wow,

00:36:32.125 --> 00:36:33.467
I'm behind a lot of people.

00:36:33.467 --> 00:36:34.800
I never would have thought that.

00:36:34.800 --> 00:36:37.660
Or I'm actually way luckier
than I thought I was.

00:36:37.660 --> 00:36:41.505
And it teaches you about who
the people you're around are

00:36:41.505 --> 00:36:42.880
and also some of
their struggles.

00:36:42.880 --> 00:36:44.713
Because some of my
classmates who were white

00:36:44.713 --> 00:36:46.780
girls were behind me.

00:36:46.780 --> 00:36:48.480
And I was like, I wonder why.

00:36:48.480 --> 00:36:49.720
So we got to unpack it.

00:36:49.720 --> 00:36:51.680
I feel like it's really
important for companies

00:36:51.680 --> 00:36:53.120
to do this.

00:36:53.120 --> 00:36:54.896
Because give your
employees a chance

00:36:54.896 --> 00:36:57.520
to understand where they are in
the world and what they fit in.

00:36:57.520 --> 00:37:00.250
Because sometimes in these
rooms, the people of color,

00:37:00.250 --> 00:37:03.174
the people who are
different, LGBT people,

00:37:03.174 --> 00:37:04.590
